  "body": "We currently to nightly \"unstable\" releases and biweekly \"alpha\" releases, however, at this early stage of the project, we do not have any strategies towards stabilizing the code and the releases.\r\n\r\nI use this meta ticket to outline some strategies to revisit in future in case we want to move into a \"beta\" or \"stable\" phase.\r\n\r\nUseful resouce: \r\n- https://hackmd.io/HOaKGHWGT-aLzF6kh1KQfA\r\n- I had this call with the Teku, Lighthouse, and Prysm teams last year\r\n- Everything in this document also applies to Lodestar obviously\r\n\r\nThe key element is the release checklist (we can already tick two boxes):\r\n> Release components checklist for teams:\r\n> - [x] dedicate a team member to commit to releases (release manager, release coordinator) --> @q9f?\r\n> - [x] commit to a strict versioning scheme (semver, calver, etc.) --> **semver** (lerna)\r\n> - [x] enable concurrent development that reflect different expectations of release quality (stable, beta, nightly, etc.)\r\n> - [x] conduct pre-release testing (release candidates, CI, QA)\r\n> - [x] distribute packages (binaries, signatures, checksums) --> **NPM/Docker**\r\n\r\nThe hackmd above also outlines two different release strategies (Flow vs. Maturity). I always give the example that Geth uses the _\"Flow\"_ strategy and Parity ~~uses~~ used _\"Maturity.\"_ I'm personally a big fan of the latter.\r\n\r\nCurrent State of Lodestar https://github.com/ChainSafe/lodestar/releases\r\n- [x] has development branches\r\n    - [x] `master` (pull requests default to `master`)\r\n- [x] has releases (23)\r\n    - [x] `v0.29.1` on :warning: `master`\r\n    - [x] `v0.29.0` on :warning: `master`\r\n    - [x] ...\r\n- [x] :warning: has release branches\r\n    - [x] :warning: no release branch for current track (0.29 ?)\r\n",
